1 petroleum product or fuel gas.
2 (9) “Fossil fuel business” means a business engaged in the extraction of fossil fuels or
3 the refining of petroleum products.
4 (10) “Fuel gas” means methane, natural gas, liquified natural gas or manufactured fuel
5 gases.
6 (11) “Greenhouse gas” has the meaning given that term in ORS 468A.210.
7 (12) “Nature-based solutions” means projects, including green or natural infrastructure
8 projects, that utilize or mimic nature or natural processes and functions and that may also
9 offer environmental, economic and social benefits while increasing climate resilience.
10 (13) “Petroleum product” means any product that is obtained from distilling, refining,
11 re-refining or processing synthetic or crude oil or crude oil extracted from natural gas liq-
12 uids or other sources.
13 (14) “Responsible party” means an entity that:
14 (a) Holds or held a majority ownership interest in a business engaged in extracting or
15 refining fossil fuel during the covered period, or is a successor in interest to the business;
16 (b) During any part of the covered period, did business in this state or otherwise had
17 sufficient contacts with this state to establish personal jurisdiction on any basis consistent
18 with the United States Constitution; and
19 (c) The Department of Environmental Quality determines is responsible for more than
20 one billion metric tons of covered greenhouse gas emissions, in aggregate globally, during the
21 covered period.
22 SECTION 2. (1) The Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program is established as an
23 interagency response to the effects of climate change. The purpose of the program is to
24 adapt to and mitigate the effects of climate change and hold responsible parties strictly liable
25 for the costs of climate change caused by covered greenhouse gas emissions.
26 (2)(a) The Department of Land Conservation and Development shall lead an interagency
27 team to carry out sections 1 to 7 of this 2026 Act.
28 (b) Any state agency shall assist or participate in the interagency team upon the request
29 of the Director of the Department of Land Conservation and Development.
30 (c) The Department of Land Conservation and Development and other state agencies
31 participating in the interagency team may enter into intergovernmental agreements as nec-
32 essary to carry out the duties of the interagency team.
33 (3)(a) State agencies participating in the interagency team shall work collaboratively to
34 carry out the purposes of the program.
35 (b) The department shall serve as the lead agency of the interagency team and shall, in
36 coordination with the interagency team:
37 (A) Develop, adopt, implement and update a resilience implementation strategy that will
38 identify eligible climate change resilience projects; and
39 (B) Provide grants or loans for eligible climate change resilience projects in accordance
40 with rules adopted by the Land Conservation and Development Commission under section 3
41 of this 2026 Act.
42 (c) The following agencies, in coordination with the department and the interagency
43 team, shall develop and implement the following portions of the resilience implementation
44 strategy:
45 (A) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall develop and implement
[2]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 those portions of the resilience implementation strategy related to disaster preparedness and
2 recovery.
3 (B) The Oregon Health Authority shall develop and implement those portions of the
4 resilience implementation strategy related to harms to public health as a result of climate
5 change, including harms resulting from extreme heat and other extreme weather events and
6 disease related to environmental conditions.
7 (C) The Department of the State Fire Marshal shall develop and implement those
8 portions of the resilience implementation strategy related to fire loss prevention and fire
9 recovery due to wildfire.
10 (d) The Department of Land Conservation and Development may direct any state agency
11 participating in the interagency team to develop or implement portions of the resilience im-
12 plementation strategy, as consistent with the agency’s existing authorities and responsibil-
13 ities.
14 (4) The Environmental Quality Commission and the Department of Environmental Qual-
15 ity shall, in coordination with the interagency team, carry out the responsibilities of the
16 commission and the department described in sections 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act.
17 SECTION 3. (1) The Land Conservation and Development Commission, in consultation
18 with the interagency team established under section 2 of this 2026 Act, shall establish by rule
19 a resilience implementation strategy that includes:
20 (a) Practices for utilizing nature-based solutions intended to stabilize floodplains, riparian
21 zones, shorelands, wetlands and similar lands;
22 (b) Practices to adapt infrastructure to the impacts of climate change, including but not
23 limited to homes, buildings and public spaces;
24 (c) Practices needed to build out early warning mechanisms and support fast, effective
25 response to climate-related threats;
26 (d) Practices that support economic and environmental sustainability in the face of
27 changing climate conditions;
28 (e) Criteria and procedures for identifying and prioritizing climate change resilience
29 projects that are consistent with the practices identified in paragraphs (a) to (d) of this
30 subsection; and
31 (f) Procedures and standards for providing grants or loans using moneys from the Cli-
32 mate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account established in section 7 of this 2026 Act for
33 eligible climate change resilience projects.
34 (2) To develop the strategy adopted by the commission under subsection (1) of this sec-
35 tion, the Department of Land Conservation and Development shall:
36 (a) Consult with the Department of Environmental Quality and the Environmental Jus-
37 tice Council;
38 (b) In coordination with the Oregon Health Authority, assess the resilience needs and
39 vulnerabilities of geographic areas that are vital to this state’s economy and the health and
40 well-being of Oregonians;
41 (c) Identify potential and proposed climate change resilience projects throughout this
42 state;
43 (d) Identify opportunities for alignment with existing federal, state and local funding
44 streams;
45 (e) Consult with local governments, the nine federally recognized Indian tribes in this
[3]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 state, businesses, environmental advocates, relevant subject area experts, representatives
2 of environmental justice communities and other stakeholders; and
3 (f) Conduct public engagement in communities that have the most significant exposure
4 to the impacts of climate change, including disadvantaged, low-income and rural communi-
5 ties.
6 (3) For purposes of determining whether a climate change resilience project benefits an
7 environmental justice community, as provided by section 7 (6) of this 2026 Act, rules adopted
8 by the commission:
9 (a) Must define a “community”:
10 (A) As a group of individuals living in geographic proximity to one another who experi-
11 ence common conditions; and
12 (B) Without reference to or consideration of the race, color, ethnicity or national origin
13 of the individuals living within the community.
14 (b) May require use of the environmental justice mapping tool developed under ORS
15 182.555.
16 SECTION 4. The Department of Land Conservation and Development, the Department
17 of Environmental Quality and the Oregon Health Authority, in consultation with other rele-
18 vant state agencies as may be necessary, shall conduct an assessment to determine the costs
19 to this state of covered greenhouse gas emissions for the covered period. The assessment
20 shall include:
21 (1) An analysis of the various cost-driving effects of covered greenhouse gas emissions
22 on the state, including the effects on public health, natural resources, biodiversity, agricul-
23 ture, first foods, economic development, flood preparedness and safety, housing and any
24 other effect that the Department of Land Conservation and Development determines is rel-
25 evant.
26 (2) A description of the costs that have been incurred and are projected to be incurred
27 as a result of the effects analyzed under subsection (1) of this section.
28 (3) A description of the costs that have been incurred and are projected to be incurred
29 to abate the effects of covered greenhouse gas emissions.
30 SECTION 5. (1) The remedies provided in sections 1 to 7 and 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act are
31 in addition to and not in lieu of any other remedy available to a person or this state at
32 common law or under state statute. Sections 1 to 7 and 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act do not:
33 (a) Relieve the liability of any entity for damages resulting from climate change under
34 any applicable law; or
35 (b) Preempt, displace or restrict any rights or remedies of a person, this state, local
36 government, as defined in ORS 174.116, or tribal government under any applicable law relat-
37 ing to a past, present or future allegation of:
38 (A) Deception concerning the effects of fossil fuels on climate change;
39 (B) Damage or injury resulting from the role of fossil fuels in contributing to climate
40 change; or
41 (C) Failure to avoid damage or injury related to climate change, including claims for
42 nuisance, trespass, design defect, negligence, failure to warn or deceptive or unfair practices.
43 (2) Sections 1 to 7 and 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act are not intended to preempt, supersede
44 or displace any other state law or local government ordinance, regulation, policy or program
45 that provides for:
[4]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 (a) Limiting, setting or enforcing standards for emissions of greenhouse gases;
2 (b) Monitoring, reporting or keeping records of greenhouse gases;
3 (c) Collecting revenue; or
4 (d) Conducting or supporting investigations.
5 (3) Nothing in sections 1 to 7 and 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act limits the existing authority
6 of any agency of state government, as defined in ORS 174.111, to regulate greenhouse gas
7 emissions or establish strategies or adopt rules to mitigate climate risk and build resilience
8 to climate change.
9 SECTION 6. The Secretary of State, in accordance with ORS 297.210, shall audit the op-
10 eration and effectiveness of the Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program no less often
11 than once every five years. Upon completing the audit, the secretary shall make recom-
12 mendations to the Department of Land Conservation and Development on ways to increase
13 program efficiency and cost effectiveness.
14 SECTION 7. (1) The Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account is established
15 in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the
16 Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account shall be credited to the account.
17 (2) The Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account consists of:
18 (a) Cost recovery payments deposited in the account under section 11 of this 2026 Act;
19 (b) Moneys appropriated or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly; and
20 (c) Grants, donations, contributions or gifts from any other public or private source.
21 (3) Moneys in the Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account are continuously
22 appropriated to the Department of Land Conservation and Development for the purposes of:
23 (a) Providing grants or loans for climate change resilience projects, or other climate
24 change resilience activities, consistent with the resilience implementation strategy estab-
25 lished under section 3 of this 2026 Act;
26 (b) Administration of sections 1 to 7 of this 2026 Act; and
27 (c) Transfer to the Department of the State Fire Marshal under subsection (4) of this
28 section.
29 (4) Thirty percent of the moneys deposited in the account each biennium shall be trans-
30 ferred to the Department of the State Fire Marshal for deposit in the Community Risk Re-
31 duction Fund established under ORS 476.396.
32 (5) At least percent of the moneys expended by the Department of Land Con-
33 servation and Development shall be for grants to the nine federally recognized Indian tribes
34 in this state.
35 (6) At least 40 percent of the moneys deposited in the account each biennium, whether
36 expended by the Department of Land Conservation and Development or the Department of
37 the State Fire Marshal, shall be expended on climate change resilience projects that benefit
38 environmental justice communities, as determined pursuant to rules adopted under section
39 3 of this 2026 Act.
40 SECTION 8. Sections 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS
41 chapter 468.
42 SECTION 9. As used in sections 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act:
43 (1) “Coal” means bituminous coal, anthracite coal and lignite.
44 (2) “Controlled group” means two or more entities treated as a single employer under:
45 (a) 26 U.S.C. 52(a) or (b), without regard to 26 U.S.C. 1563(b)(2)(C); or
[5]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 (b) 26 U.S.C. 414(m) or (o).
2 (3) “Cost recovery demand” means a charge assessed against a responsible party for cost
3 recovery payments under sections 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act.
4 (4) “Covered greenhouse gas emissions” means the total quantity of greenhouse gases
5 released into the atmosphere during the covered period, expressed in metric tons of carbon
6 dioxide equivalent, resulting from the use of fossil fuels extracted or refined by an entity.
7 (5) “Covered period” means the period beginning on January 1, 1995, and ending on De-
8 cember 31, 2024.
9 (6) “Crude oil” means oil or petroleum of any kind and in any form, including bitumen,
10 oil sands, heavy oil, conventional and unconventional oil, shale oil, natural gas liquids,
11 condensates and related fossil fuels.
12 (7) “Entity” means any individual, trustee, agent, partnership, association, corporation,
13 company, municipality, political subdivision or other legal organization, including a foreign
14 nation, that holds or held an ownership interest in a fossil fuel business during the covered
15 period.
16 (8) “Fossil fuel” means coal, a petroleum product or fuel gas or a byproduct of coal, a
17 petroleum product or fuel gas.
18 (9) “Fossil fuel business” means a business engaged in the extraction of fossil fuels or
19 the refining of petroleum products.
20 (10) “Fuel gas” means methane, natural gas, liquified natural gas or manufactured fuel
21 gases.
22 (11) “Greenhouse gas” has the meaning given that term in ORS 468A.210.
23 (12) “Notice of cost recovery demand” means the written communication from the De-
24 partment of Environmental Quality informing a responsible party of the amount of the cost
25 recovery demand.
26 (13) “Petroleum product” means any product that is obtained from distilling, refining,
27 re-refining or processing synthetic or crude oil or crude oil extracted from natural gas liq-
28 uids or other sources.
29 (14) “Responsible party” means an entity that:
30 (a) Holds or held a majority ownership interest in a business engaged in extracting or
31 refining fossil fuel during the covered period, or is a successor in interest to the business;
32 (b) During any part of the covered period, did business in this state or otherwise had
33 sufficient contacts with this state to establish personal jurisdiction on any basis consistent
34 with the United States Constitution; and
35 (c) The department determines is responsible for more than one billion metric tons of
36 covered greenhouse gas emissions, in aggregate globally, during the covered period.
37 SECTION 10. The Environmental Quality Commission shall establish by rule:
38 (1)(a) Methodologies using the best available science and publicly available data to iden-
39 tify responsible parties and determine their applicable share of covered greenhouse gas
40 emissions.
41 (b) In adopting rules under this subsection, the commission may consider emissions fac-
42 tors developed by the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
43 (2) Procedures for registering entities that are responsible parties and issuing notices of
44 cost recovery demands under section 11 of this 2026 Act.
45 (3) Procedures for collecting cost recovery demands under section 11 of this 2026 Act.
[6]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 (4) Rules of procedure for appeals to the Director of the Department of Environmental
2 Quality under section 12 of this 2026 Act.
3 SECTION 11. (1) A responsible party shall be strictly liable for the costs of climate
4 change caused by the responsible party’s covered greenhouse gas emissions, as determined
5 under subsection (2) of this section.
6 (2) The cost recovery demand for each responsible party shall be an amount equal to the
7 responsible party’s proportionate share of costs to this state, as determined under section 4
8 of this 2026 Act, from the emission of covered greenhouse gases, computed by multiplying
9 the applicable costs by the ratio of the responsible party’s covered greenhouse gas emissions
10 to all covered greenhouse gas emissions.
11 (3) To determine the amount of covered greenhouse gas emissions attributable to any
12 entity, the Department of Environmental Quality shall use the best publicly available fossil
13 fuel volume data and the methodologies developed by the Environmental Quality Commission
14 under section 10 of this 2026 Act.
15 (4) For purposes of this section, all entities in a controlled group shall be:
16 (a) Treated as a single entity for the purpose of identifying a responsible entity; and
17 (b) Jointly and severally liable for payment of any cost recovery demand owed by any
18 entity in the controlled group.
19 (5) If a responsible party owns a minority interest of 10 percent or more in another entity
20 that engaged in extracting or refining fossil fuel during the covered period, the responsible
21 party’s applicable share of covered greenhouse gas emissions shall be increased by the ap-
22 plicable share of covered greenhouse gas emissions for the entity in which the responsible
23 party holds a minority interest multiplied by the percentage of the minority interest held by
24 the responsible party.
25 (6) The department may adjust the cost recovery demand of a responsible party that re-
26 fined petroleum products or that is a successor in interest to an entity that refined petro-
27 leum products if the responsible party establishes to the satisfaction of the department that:
28 (a) A portion of the cost recovery demand amount was attributable to the refining of
29 crude oil extracted by another entity; and
30 (b) The greenhouse gas emissions attributable to the crude oil extracted by the other
31 entity was accounted for when the department determined the cost recovery demand amount
32 for the other entity or a successor in interest of the other entity.
33 (7) Except as provided in subsections (8) and (9) of this section, a responsible party shall
34 pay the cost recovery demand in full not later than six months following the date of issuance
35 of the notice of cost recovery demand.
36 (8) A responsible party may elect to pay the cost recovery demand in nine annual pay-
37 ments as follows:
38 (a) A first payment equal to 20 percent of the total cost recovery demand shall be paid
39 no later than six months from the date of issuance of the notice of cost recovery demand.
40 (b) Each subsequent payment shall be equal to 10 percent of the total cost recovery de-
41 mand and shall be due each year no later than the anniversary of the first payment. The
42 department may adjust the amount of payments described in this paragraph to reflect any
43 percentage changes in the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers, West Region (All
44 Items), as published by the Bureau of Labor Statistics of the United States Department of
45 Labor.
[7]

A-Eng. SB 1541
1 (9)(a) The unpaid balance of a cost recovery demand shall become due immediately if:
2 (A) A responsible party fails to pay any installment in a timely manner, as specified by
3 the commission by rule;
4 (B) Except as provided in paragraph (b) of this subsection, there is a liquidation or sale
5 of all or substantially all of the assets of the responsible party; or
6 (C) The responsible party ceases to do business.
7 (b) In the case of a sale of all or substantially all of the assets of a responsible party, the
8 remaining payments do not become due immediately if the buyer enters into an agreement
9 with the department to assume liability for the remaining payments due under subsection
10 (8) of this section.
11 (10) The department shall deposit cost recovery demand payments collected under this
12 section in a suspense account established under ORS 293.445 for the purpose of receiving the
13 demand payments. The department may pay the actual expenses of the department for the
14 administration and enforcement of sections 9 to 12 of this 2026 Act out of moneys received
15 from cost recovery demand payments. Amounts necessary to pay administrative and
16 enforcement expenses are continuously appropriated to the department from the suspense
17 account.
18 (11) After payment of administrative and enforcement expenses under subsection (10) of
19 this section and refunds or credits arising from erroneous overpayments, the department
20 shall transfer the balance of the moneys received from cost recovery demand payments to
21 the Climate Superfund Cost Recovery Program Account established under section 7 of this
22 2026 Act.
23 SECTION 12. A responsible party aggrieved by the issuance of a notice of cost recovery
24 demand may appeal by filing a notice of appeal with the Director of the Department of En-
25 vironmental Quality within 30 days following issuance of the notice of cost recovery demand.
26 After considering the appeal, the director shall cancel the notice of cost recovery demand
27 or affirm or adjust the cost recovery demand and issue a final notice of cost recovery de-
28 mand. A person aggrieved by a final notice of cost recovery demand may seek judicial review
29 of the notice in the manner provided by ORS chapter 183 for judicial review of orders other
30 than contested cases.
31 SECTION 13. The Department of Land Conservation and Development, the Department
32 of Environmental Quality and the Oregon Health Authority shall complete the assessment
33 described in section 4 of this 2026 Act no later than January 1, 2029. The Department of Land
34 Conservation and Development shall include the assessment in a report submitted in the
35 manner provided by ORS 192.245 to the Joint Interim Committee on Ways and Means and the
36 interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to finance, revenue, natural re-
37 sources and the environment.
38 SECTION 14. (1) The Land Conservation and Development Commission shall first adopt
39 rules under section 3 of this 2026 Act no later than January 1, 2029.
40 (2) The Environmental Quality Commission shall first adopt rules under section 10 of this
41 2026 Act no later than January 1, 2029.
42 SECTION 15. In addition to and not in lieu of any other appropriation, there is appro-
43 priated to the Department of Land Conservation and Development, for the biennium ending
44 June 30, 2027, out of the General Fund, the amount of $300,000, which may be expended for
45 the purpose of carrying out sections 1 to 7 of this 2026 Act.
[8]

